---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import { localePath } from "../../i18n";
import { GITHUB_URL } from "../../lib/site";
const lang = "en" as const;
---

<Base lang={lang} title="About & how to contribute — Recompendium" description="What Recompendium is, what counts as a recomp, and how to add a project with a Pull Request.">
  <main class="wrap detail">
    <div class="crumb"><a href={localePath(lang, "")}>← Catalog</a></div>
    <h1>About Recompendium</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      A community-driven, multi-console, filterable catalog of <b>static recompilations</b>: the
      process that turns a console game's original binary into native PC code. It's not emulation
      and not a hand-written decompilation — it's translating the executable to C/C++ and compiling
      it for your machine.
    </p>

    <div class="sec-h"><h2>What's in and what's out</h2></div>
    <p style="color:var(--ink-2);max-width:72ch">
      The <b>Catalog</b> brings together four kinds of project: <b>static recompilations</b>
      (N64Recomp, XenonRecomp, ReXGlue…), <a href={localePath(lang, "ports")} style="color:var(--gold)">ports &amp; remakes</a>
      based on decompilation or made by fans (Ship of Harkinian, P-06…), the
      <a href={localePath(lang, "decompilaciones")} style="color:var(--gold)">decompilations</a> themselves
      —the original code reversed to source, synced from decomp.dev— and the
      <a href={localePath(lang, "launchers")} style="color:var(--gold)">tools</a> that make it all possible.
    </p>

    <div class="sec-h"><h2>Recomp vs. decompilation</h2></div>
    <p style="color:var(--ink-2);max-width:72ch">
      A <b>recompilation</b> translates the game's binary into native code and is playable now. A
      <b>decompilation</b> is the step before: it reverses that binary into readable source, byte-matching
      the original; once mature, native ports grow from it. That's why we list both, but kept apart —
      a recomp is playable; a 30%-decompiled project isn't yet. Each decompilation's % is synced live from decomp.dev.
    </p>

    <div class="sec-h"><h2>A bit of history</h2></div>
    <p style="color:var(--ink-2);max-width:72ch">
      The first full, playable game recomp was <b>Zelda 64: Recompiled</b> (Majora's Mask), by Mr.
      Wiseguy, in <b>May 2024</b>, built on N64Recomp. It was also the first to ship a built-in
      <b>launcher</b>. The wave grew fast: Banjo (January 2025, with a very polished
      launcher/mod-manager), the first standalone universal launcher (N64RecompLauncher, Aug. 2025),
      and the Xbox 360 explosion with XenonRecomp and, more recently, ReXGlue.
    </p>

    <div class="sec-h"><h2>Want to add or fix something?</h2></div>
    <p style="color:var(--ink-2);max-width:72ch">
      No coding needed. Use the
      <a href={localePath(lang, "contribuir")} style="color:var(--gold)">Contribute</a> form —or the
      <b>Edit</b> button on any entry— and fill in the fields in your language. Your proposal comes
      in as a suggestion we <b>review by hand</b> before publishing: we complete the missing
      translation, and stars and dates update automatically from GitHub.
    </p>

    <div class="actions" style="margin-top:18px">
      <a class="btn primary" href={localePath(lang, "contribuir")}>Contribute</a>
      <a class="btn" href={localePath(lang, "faq")}>FAQ</a>
      <a class="btn" href={GITHUB_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Repository ↗</a>
    </div>

    <p class="legal" style="margin-top:30px">
      Recompendium does not host or link ROMs or copyrighted assets. Every recomp requires your own
      legal copy of the game.
    </p>
  </main>
</Base>
